<subSubSection id="F7E992A463A601F6DD13A5DC092CAA23" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6F0AD6C6F098197A397969D4C5920C42" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F63E9FD515C25197521ECA17D80A243E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body size: male 7-13 mm, female 9-14 mm. The triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum place this species in a group together with 
<taxonomicName id="62F4737C47011FE8B99C14D933E09099" genus="P." lsidName="P. aureus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureus">
<emphasis id="1881962E54EC3806BE55D2DA6DD017C5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="64B3586E3CA36831A5D5F21C23B5B726" genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis id="B922EA4C093877C153F0DA653D1A1A0A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="3E096811E59130EFE9D161EEBBAA0C68" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="3628A17A44D9426BB25CCD8C51C1AACD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. From the first two species, 
<taxonomicName id="CC80CE7B278894878D632F568551E91B" genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis id="C797E606E1A9BF8560B9AD637EC1679D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the presence of golden pile along the anterior and lateral margins of the mesoscutum. The male differs from 
<taxonomicName id="2A4276B78E80F562BDB86AAC60F2CDFA" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="4E9C60BD432861D047213D13B20AE53C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by tergite 2 being widened posteriorly (parallel-sided in 
<taxonomicName id="D31565333B3E8AB107F0B92F92BDBAA3" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="FD48BF1B65C3E5CCD803792D6E70D43B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and by sternite 4 being evenly convex and short pilose (with bulge-like, long pilose tubercle in 
<taxonomicName id="CE523332DED67631E8BBD594ACEE9D78" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="634B3A7E5B22B939EE7E1FFE82931EA0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Male genitalia as in 
<figureCitation id="8D6EC766067B41AB98E424F9C694B666" captionStart="Figures 256–261" captionStartId="F44" captionText="Figures 256 - 261. Male genitalia of Peradon species 256 P. fenestratus French Guyana MNHN 257 P. aureoscutus holotype 258 P. aureus Ecuador CNC 259 P. trilinea holotype 260 P. trivittatus Suriname RMNH 261 P. hermetia holotype." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures256-261" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362314" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures256-261">Fig. 260</figureCitation>
. The female differs from 
<taxonomicName id="A35A3C8F44FF45AC831294619D083E07" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="5DE32B42433DE2E830F1C199D6FC5C81" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by sternite 3 being more or less flat and only narrowly separated from sternite 4 (instead of strongly arched and with wide intermediate membrane in 
<taxonomicName id="4DB1C3FA3D42E6AD192C4136FD565CF3" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="B23A86A9E0CBACECBF2A2894F1BCF74F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="234C4BD900CC12210E5C730A189241DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="5F50789D21559371F9553BD86DE364E1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C43BCCDB0EDF1E9C90344E0603AB162F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body size variation is considerable in this species. The smallest males (known from Venezuela and the Brazilian state of Amazonas) measure only 7 or 8 mm, which at first sight gives the impression that they belong to a different species. However, many intermediates occur between these 
<normalizedToken id="4811CE90D78157D0244E9EC79535978D" originalValue="‘dwarfs’">'dwarfs'</normalizedToken>
and the largest specimens, and all specimens are very similar in morphology and colouration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17C3CC5CA82208C5F689A69FC8F82CE7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6E894DE5ED05EBFE19720B3EFF98B86E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A5BBD8277E01BA95916B141E2C836864" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Known from Amazonian parts of Brazil, Colombia, Peru, Suriname, and Venezuela.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
